 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8079664251944246`*^9, 3.8079664343142004`*^9}, {
   3.8079689400739555`*^9, 3.8079689680029573`*^9}, {3.807970315263204*^9, 
   3.8079703215316095`*^9}, {3.807970415909548*^9, 3.807970437015459*^9}, {
   3.8079705221296997`*^9, 3.8079705895237727`*^9}, {3.809503913366911*^9, 
   3.809503915415073*^9}, 3.80950418131592*^9, {3.810634811313981*^9, 
   3.8106348242505617`*^9}, {3.8106348784099083`*^9, 
   3.8106348981796308`*^9}, {3.8106349903838186`*^9, 
   3.8106350062466736`*^9}, {3.8106350462927155`*^9, 
   3.8106350558036213`*^9}, {3.810635166709814*^9, 3.8106351767461023`*^9}, {
   3.8106356178156724`*^9, 3.8106356424120965`*^9}, {3.8119381719563165`*^9, 
   3.8119381823242064`*^9}, {3.814548711850298*^9, 
   3.8145487426667533`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1bd89049-6c14-4c20-889e-\
731875d277d6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["H",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], 
   RowBox[{"(", "0", ")"}]]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8079664251944246`*^9, 3.8079664343142004`*^9}, {
    3.8079689400739555`*^9, 3.8079689680029573`*^9}, {3.807970315263204*^9, 
    3.8079703215316095`*^9}, {3.807970415909548*^9, 3.807970437015459*^9}, {
    3.8079705221296997`*^9, 3.8079705895237727`*^9}, {3.809503913366911*^9, 
    3.809503915415073*^9}, 3.80950418131592*^9, {3.810634811313981*^9, 
    3.8106348242505617`*^9}, {3.8106348784099083`*^9, 
    3.8106348981796308`*^9}, {3.8106349903838186`*^9, 
    3.8106350062466736`*^9}, {3.8106350462927155`*^9, 
    3.8106350558036213`*^9}, {3.810635166709814*^9, 3.8106351767461023`*^9}, {
    3.8106356178156724`*^9, 3.8106356424120965`*^9}, {3.8119381719563165`*^9, 
    3.8119381823242064`*^9}, {3.814548711850298*^9, 3.8145487426667533`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"46d5880d-0ddc-4035-ad72-f3d3f496307a"],
 "arises from a Fock operator, and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["H",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], 
    RowBox[{"(", "1", ")"}]],
   FontSlant->"Italic"]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8079664251944246`*^9, 3.8079664343142004`*^9}, {
    3.8079689400739555`*^9, 3.8079689680029573`*^9}, {3.807970315263204*^9, 
    3.8079703215316095`*^9}, {3.807970415909548*^9, 3.807970437015459*^9}, {
    3.8079705221296997`*^9, 3.8079705895237727`*^9}, {3.809503913366911*^9, 
    3.809503915415073*^9}, 3.80950418131592*^9, {3.810634811313981*^9, 
    3.8106348242505617`*^9}, {3.8106348784099083`*^9, 
    3.8106348981796308`*^9}, {3.8106349903838186`*^9, 
    3.8106350062466736`*^9}, {3.8106350462927155`*^9, 
    3.8106350558036213`*^9}, {3.810635166709814*^9, 3.8106351767461023`*^9}, {
    3.8106356178156724`*^9, 3.8106356424120965`*^9}, {3.8119381719563165`*^9, 
    3.8119381823242064`*^9}, {3.814548711850298*^9, 3.8145487426667533`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"643e2dbb-e0ac-492c-a4ae-2329a544ef11"],
 "is known as the correlation potential. The most popular type of calculation \
is a second-order perturbation, known as MP2, but there are also higher-order \
perturbations (MP3, MP4, etc.). "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8145486840325317`*^9, 3.814548684954212*^9}, {
  3.8145487472413907`*^9, 
  3.814548840183914*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"48712321-22ec-4006-8039-\
795eb045a189"],

Cell["\<\
Density Functional Theory \[Dash] perhaps the most ubiquitous method in \
computational chemistry, this method is relatively cheap (meaning \
computationally quick) and accurate. There are numerous approximations within \
density functional theory, all of which use a slightly different combination \
of terms to estimate the electronic structure. Some of the most common \
approaches include B3LYP, PBE0, M06, and \[Omega]B97X.\
\>", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814598921083621*^9, 3.8145990858003435`*^9}, {
  3.8145997614514446`*^9, 3.8145998060970583`*^9}, {3.8145999692018237`*^9, 
  3.8145999755409966`*^9}, {3.814600276166855*^9, 
  3.8146002794589806`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1fe7ea39-052b-4ac8-b296-\
5c42862e6874"],

Cell["\<\
Coupled cluster calculations \[Dash] this approach also typically begins with \
the Hartree-Fock solutions and then takes a linear combination of the slater \
determinants of excited states. One approximation in particular, CCSD(T), is \
considered the gold standard for calculations on ground-state, closed-shell \
molecules. This approach is generally very expensive and can only be used for \
small molecules.\
\>", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814598921083621*^9, 3.814599092647273*^9}, {
  3.814599319287125*^9, 3.814599357273224*^9}, {3.814599406312818*^9, 
  3.8145995136631107`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"79ea1389-2117-405a-9147-\
3c1e0a2100e2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["ab initio",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " Molecular Dynamics (AIMD) \[Dash] this approach involves a combination of \
traditional molecular dynamics, which don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t account for \
quantum mechanical effects, and electronic structure methods (MP2, DFT, \
etc.). It enables a more accurate, quantum-mechanical description of system \
dynamics, but it can\[CloseCurlyQuote]t account for nuclear quantum effects \
such as zero-point energy. There is a somewhat related method, ring polymer \
molecular dynamics (RPMD), that can account for nuclear quantum effects but \
is much more expensive."
}], "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814598921083621*^9, 3.814599092647273*^9}, {
  3.814599319287125*^9, 3.814599357273224*^9}, {3.814599406312818*^9, 
  3.8145996414156036`*^9}, {3.8145996795600686`*^9, 
  3.8145997175089493`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9a84363f-6dae-46c4-a4b1-\
df9efaaac682"],

Cell["\<\
These approaches are some of the most common employed for studying \
ground-state systems. To accurately predict electronic excited states, more \
advanced approaches are typically required.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8145997250306125`*^9, 3.814599753147066*^9}, {
  3.8146002878291693`*^9, 
  3.814600325967784*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"af69a95a-2fd1-43a1-bd8d-\
3475d49e353e"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Choose a Basis Set", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8145416244643707`*^9, 3.8145416273837705`*^9}, {
  3.814600392788229*^9, 
  3.8146003946872396`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0247ae01-a27b-42fd-b61d-\
3a308dd80a5f"],

Cell["\<\
All of the methods listed above take a linear combination of atomic orbitals \
approach to solving for the molecular orbitals. The term \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]atomic orbitals\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] here does not \
represent the true atomic orbitals of an atom but rather an approximation \
formed by a basis set. The choice of basis set thus determines whether the \
full accuracy of the method can be achieved. If a basis set is too small, the \
results will be highly inaccurate because the molecular orbitals cannot be \
constructed. If it\[CloseCurlyQuote]s too large, the calculation will take \
too long to be practically useful. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146003512947917`*^9, 3.814600357243389*^9}, {
   3.8146003984309144`*^9, 3.8146005636235657`*^9}, 
   3.8146014756695237`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"70546827-ed1a-42d9-adb3-\
98c4f62a39f6"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

