Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Figure 12.2.",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " Fitting of a Slater-type function by a linear combination of Gaussian \
functions."
}], "Affiliation",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809435027311596*^9, 3.8094350763900714`*^9}, {
   3.80943583474421*^9, 3.8094358359299717`*^9}, {3.8094472165104203`*^9, 
   3.809447281165168*^9}, {3.810054221304062*^9, 3.8100542409148703`*^9}, {
   3.8101125924447937`*^9, 3.8101126426025887`*^9}, {3.8101127071459217`*^9, 
   3.810112714050138*^9}, {3.810115126505663*^9, 3.810115154403865*^9}, {
   3.8101152097595587`*^9, 3.8101152368678613`*^9}, {3.8104844563968916`*^9, 
   3.8104844576598825`*^9}, {3.81193141565689*^9, 3.8119315300297594`*^9}, {
   3.8119337071325006`*^9, 3.811933740644105*^9}, {3.8119343804898696`*^9, 
   3.811934419448634*^9}, {3.811934465780332*^9, 3.8119344672733955`*^9}, {
   3.8119350679013205`*^9, 3.811935086595256*^9}, {3.814614320484557*^9, 
   3.814614322854318*^9}, {3.814614379345688*^9, 3.8146144110438213`*^9}, 
   3.8148824470841537`*^9, 
   3.9392061434229145`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"6b7ac3e3-a36a-45ab-9e03-\
6eb920eeb0d7"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Minimal Basis Sets", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814618386353504*^9, 
  3.814618392746761*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c6a0e63f-2712-4911-800c-\
5aa6b6ac92b2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A minimal basis set includes only one basis function for each orbital in \
the Hartree-Fock (or similar) calculation. For ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["2", "nd"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7f1a8b6c-7983-48a7-975f-2da3c8d88f63"],
 "-row atoms, a minimal basis set also includes all of the ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "-type orbitals. For example, the minimal basis for a hydrogen atom would \
include only one 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbital, whereas the minimal basis for a carbon atom would include \
the 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"2", 
    SubscriptBox["p", "x"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a8f1ec9d-321c-49b7-bd24-80ebb9518a8f"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"2", 
    SubscriptBox["p", "y"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "2a2e9cbf-6ae4-47d9-8108-c550ae3c245c"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"2", 
    SubscriptBox["p", "z"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4d01ee3a-4be8-48e1-9100-1e441607b668"],
 " orbitals. Basis sets such as STO\[Dash]3G and STO\[Dash]6G are minimal \
basis sets. These really aren\[CloseCurlyQuote]t used very often in modern \
computational chemistry."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146183955140915`*^9, 3.8146184535089293`*^9}, {
  3.8146184955041366`*^9, 3.814618614987109*^9}, {3.814619241897385*^9, 
  3.8146192858019333`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8187ca36-56ae-4342-89af-\
07a09d5c7eef"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Double-Zeta, Triple-Zeta, and Split-Valence Basis Sets", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146194560286355`*^9, 3.814619459264135*^9}, {
  3.814619800687931*^9, 3.8146198143289375`*^9}, {3.814621595263379*^9, 
  3.8146215986299863`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5c180a61-8444-4975-bbd5-\
020a171302fa"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Minimal basis sets struggle to accurately predict molecular structure and \
properties because they cannot sufficiently account for the full shape of the \
molecular orbitals. In particular, they inaccurately predict asymmetric \
bonding in polyatomic molecules, where the electron density of different \
bonds of an atomic center is asymmetric due to bonding with atoms of \
different electronegativity. This problem can be rectified by including \
multiple basis functions for each atomic orbital. For example, for a 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbital, a double-zeta basis set would include the functions"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146198171255083`*^9, 3.814619843698283*^9}, {
   3.8146198821594996`*^9, 3.814620058146745*^9}, {3.8146201017324495`*^9, 
   3.814620150196579*^9}, 3.814620263654855*^9, {3.814682384874887*^9, 
   3.8146824097430506`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2687a2a7-be38-4cc4-871d-\
4169fd479d22"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SubscriptBox["\[Phi]", 
   RowBox[{"2", 
    StyleBox["s",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]}]], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["a",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "1"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Phi]", 
     RowBox[{"2", 
      StyleBox["s",
       FontSlant->"Italic"]}], "GTO"], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Zeta]",
        FontSlant->"Plain"], "1"], ",", 
      StyleBox["r",
       FontSlant->"Italic"]}], ")"}]}], "+", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["a",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "2"], 
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Phi]", 
     RowBox[{"2", 
      StyleBox["s",
       FontSlant->"Italic"]}], "GTO"], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Zeta]",
        FontSlant->"Plain"], "2"], ",", 
      StyleBox["r",
       FontSlant->"Italic"]}], ")"}]}]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814620181040546*^9, 
  3.8146202433047557`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"47edbcfb-b53d-487f-9d64-\
ae877914b425"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "where the weighting coefficients ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["a",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "1"]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814620181040546*^9, 3.8146202433047557`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"8bf7002c-0268-41dc-a374-3de6745496df"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["a",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "2"]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.814620181040546*^9, 3.8146202433047557`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"5c2b43ca-b837-4f17-9488-ff7264be2871"],
 " would be optimized for a given molecular orbital. There are also \
triple-zeta basis sets and even quadruple-zeta or even higher basis sets."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146202841280327`*^9, 3.8146203072781167`*^9}, {
  3.8146203430187063`*^9, 
  3.814620367991797*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"05960a2f-0442-437e-bc15-\
44664fb8e4de"],

Cell["\<\
To prevent double- or triple-zeta basis sets from becoming so large as to be \
computationally intractable, calculations are often performed with \
split-valence basis sets, in which the core electrons are represented by a \
minimal basis set, whereas the valence electrons are represented by a double- \
or triple-zeta basis set.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146204352530317`*^9, 3.814620454658334*^9}, {
  3.8146206184370117`*^9, 3.8146206671787815`*^9}, {3.8146214924841256`*^9, 
  3.814621503067587*^9}, {3.8146215440890665`*^9, 
  3.814621614022905*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c37cb491-d9d0-48c0-9705-\
691f657bd33a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note that when using these basis sets, the values of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Zeta]", "i"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "16f129e2-432a-4671-a903-c7c9e20bda99"],
 " are fixed for a given atom. In addition, the weighting factor ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["a", "1"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "deaac144-14d5-4a7b-8f32-c3946b82a179"],
 " is typically fixed (this may in fact comprise several weighting factors \
for different Gaussian components), and the factor ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["a", "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b1f10504-9f42-4e96-97c0-08721e0f61f3"],
 " is varied as part of the optimization. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146353374098706`*^9, 3.8146354116382294`*^9}, {
  3.814635599284038*^9, 3.814635603114944*^9}, {3.8146356833604765`*^9, 
  3.814635737666418*^9}, {3.8146357695709066`*^9, 
  3.8146357700223465`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0db1b241-c004-4069-8e4a-\
62fd052497e2"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Pople Basis Sets", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814621688354157*^9, 
  3.814621693452651*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2015904f-5e36-45f1-a31c-\
90c1188c5db4"],

Cell["\<\
There are many forms of split-valence basis sets, but some of the \
historically most popular basis sets are those developed by John Pople and \
co-workers. The nomenclature for these basis sets is\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146216956837234`*^9, 3.8146217010449276`*^9}, {
  3.814622044613426*^9, 3.814622074833195*^9}, {3.8146818944470997`*^9, 
  3.8146818954409304`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a2dc9ebd-e935-41a7-8034-\
b18850698406"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  StyleBox["n",
   FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[Dash]", 
  StyleBox[
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["mp",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], 
    StyleBox["G",
     FontSlant->"Plain"]}]]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814620181040546*^9, 3.8146202433047557`*^9}, {
  3.814622082294969*^9, 
  3.8146220956104608`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1162291b-efe1-45b1-a384-\
d937f8faa715"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "where ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " specifies the number of Gaussians terms in the core basis functions (STO\
\[Dash]",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "G), and ",
 StyleBox["m",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " give the number of Gaussian primitives used to construct each double-zeta \
valence orbital. In other words, each valence atomic orbital is constructed \
of two basis functions, one with ",
 StyleBox["m",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " primitive gaussian functions (typically optimized as a \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]contracted\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] orbital) and one \
with ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " primitive gaussian functions (optimized for an \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]extended\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] orbital). "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146220987317734`*^9, 3.8146221556314955`*^9}, {
  3.814622307516382*^9, 3.8146223805230503`*^9}, {3.8146226503428087`*^9, 
  3.8146227181231003`*^9}, {3.8146819937149773`*^9, 
  3.8146820318980355`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"21360b33-3e0a-4190-a5cf-\
2e293b7f529b"],

Cell["\<\
One of the most popular Pople basis sets is 6-31G, which has a STO-6G \
representation for each core atomic orbital, and valence orbitals constructed \
from two basis functions (a double-zeta basis), one which is a linear \
combination of three Gaussian functions and one which is just a single \
Gaussian function. Another popular basis set is 6-311G, which is a bit newer \
and doesn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t quite follow the nomenclature above; the extra \
one represents an additional orbital component (triple-zeta basis) with just \
one Gaussian primitive.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814622719577927*^9, 3.8146228795101733`*^9}, {
  3.814635313866191*^9, 3.8146353202019634`*^9}, {3.8146822687086334`*^9, 
  3.8146822874675703`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"fbf8de22-d8d0-41e9-90c3-\
0927b400c8bc"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Polarization and Diffuse Functions", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146359475288677`*^9, 
  3.814635951308951*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3e0f3bf8-c520-46ef-95c8-\
39d67114f229"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Although we have used double- and triple-zeta basis sets to address the \
issue of differences in electron density between different bonds (different \
atoms binding to a central carbon, for example), we haven\[CloseCurlyQuote]t \
yet addressed the polarization inherent in forming a molecular bond, which \
distorts the symmetric electron density around an atom. Take the example of a \
\[Sigma] bond in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["H",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "2a095bc1-2593-428c-a790-d951a2dc0361"],
 ", where the electron density about each hydrogen is not spherically \
symmetric. To account for this asymmetry, we can include an additional 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbital, which can then be added to the previous basis of a 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbital to create a molecular orbital that is asymmetric with respect to \
hydrogen. Such additional atomic orbitals in a basis set are known as \
polarization functions. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146361929294643`*^9, 3.814636523570778*^9}, {
  3.8148903342512536`*^9, 
  3.814890335588297*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7774660a-772d-46e5-8473-\
ceb7e66edecd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The above example relates to polarization of ",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbitals by addition of ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "-type orbitals. Similarly, ",
 StyleBox["d",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "-type orbitals can be added to ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "-type orbitals to generate polarized orbitals, as shown in Figure 12.3"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814890344113586*^9, 3.814890407287771*^9}, 
   3.9392061441324825`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"5f5ec376-0eab-481f-9235-\
c31ff2dfe3fc"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Import", "[", 
  "\"\<https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a7/D-polarization_\
function.png\>\"", "]"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8148904214144907`*^9, 3.8148904371894474`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[84]:=",ExpressionUUID->"00303cce-7e52-490e-8a1c-f788e0e1df13"],

