Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Figure 12.3.",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " Linear combination of ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["d",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals to generate a polarized ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbital. Wikimedia, Rifleman82, CC BY-SA 3.0, \
https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:D-polarization_function.png"
}], "Affiliation",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809435027311596*^9, 3.8094350763900714`*^9}, {
   3.80943583474421*^9, 3.8094358359299717`*^9}, {3.8094472165104203`*^9, 
   3.809447281165168*^9}, {3.810054221304062*^9, 3.8100542409148703`*^9}, {
   3.8101125924447937`*^9, 3.8101126426025887`*^9}, {3.8101127071459217`*^9, 
   3.810112714050138*^9}, {3.810115126505663*^9, 3.810115154403865*^9}, {
   3.8101152097595587`*^9, 3.8101152368678613`*^9}, {3.8104844563968916`*^9, 
   3.8104844576598825`*^9}, {3.81193141565689*^9, 3.8119315300297594`*^9}, {
   3.8119337071325006`*^9, 3.811933740644105*^9}, {3.8119343804898696`*^9, 
   3.811934419448634*^9}, {3.811934465780332*^9, 3.8119344672733955`*^9}, {
   3.8119350679013205`*^9, 3.811935086595256*^9}, {3.814614320484557*^9, 
   3.814614322854318*^9}, {3.814614379345688*^9, 3.8146144110438213`*^9}, {
   3.8148824470841537`*^9, 3.814882507024972*^9}, {3.8148904794705067`*^9, 
   3.8148905501699524`*^9}, 
   3.9392061448632355`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"b8d738d6-a676-4ead-9ace-\
e3bf4affd2d9"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Different basis sets utilize different terminology to denote the addition \
of polarization functions. A useful table is provided at ",
 ButtonBox["https://gaussian.com/basissets/",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://gaussian.com/basissets/"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://gaussian.com/basissets/"],
 ". For the Pople basis sets, the polarization functions are noted with the \
terminology (d, p), where the d symbol denotes the addition of one set of 3",
 StyleBox["d",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals to the basis of second-row elements, and the p specifies the \
addition of one set of 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals to the hydrogen and/or helium atoms. Previously, an older \
nomenclature of ** was used (where the first star corresponds to d and the \
second star corresponds to p). "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814636530126536*^9, 3.814636614593557*^9}, {
  3.8146366550702553`*^9, 3.814636765379258*^9}, {3.8147006654374595`*^9, 
  3.8147006676079073`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a1c3df28-3af4-4462-97f6-\
c365fb1e0cd1"],

Cell["\<\
Recall that the Gaussian-type orbitals do not accurately depict the shape of \
the wavefunction at large distances from the nucleus (see, for example, \
Figure 12.1). To provide a more accurate depiction of the electron density at \
large distances from the nucleus, we can add additional diffuse functions to \
the basis set. These functions have a small value of the exponent \[Zeta], \
meaning that the electron is likely to be found far from the nucleus. Such \
basis functions are especially important for calculating the structure of \
anions and molecules containing highly electronegative atoms such as \
fluorine. In the Pople basis sets, the addition of diffuse functions is \
indicated by a + sign or two + signs (e.g. 6-311+G(d,p)).\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8146367896430535`*^9, 3.8146368210947895`*^9}, 
   3.814639535753728*^9, 3.814882448589444*^9, 
   3.939206145842369*^9},ExpressionUUID->"1c8dad21-2015-480f-965f-\
912f15e84be4"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Correlation-Consistent Basis Sets", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8148760681808643`*^9, 3.814876071534773*^9}, {
  3.8148809071058855`*^9, 
  3.814880908583789*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ad56993a-04b7-46b8-aaa9-\
fd4d7300d8b3"],

Cell["\<\
Another widely utilized class of basis sets are the correlation-consistent \
basis sets developed by Thom Dunning and co-workers. Because the Pople basis \
sets were first optimized at the Hartree-Fock level of theory, there was \
concern that these basis sets might not be ideal for computations that \
account for electron correlation, such as MP2, CCSD(T), and DFT. The \
correlation-consistent (cc) basis sets were optimized using configuration \
interaction calculations that take into account electron correlation.  \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814880936158783*^9, 3.814880960139732*^9}, {
  3.8148811198537965`*^9, 3.8148813993789186`*^9}, {3.814881434583315*^9, 
  3.8148814547195635`*^9}, {3.8148823742512627`*^9, 
  3.8148823880253444`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"23a221fc-e5b4-4367-9e98-\
259b03009063"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The Dunning correlation-consistent basis sets are split-valence basis sets \
that add additional basis functions in \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]shells\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] when increasing the number of basis functions. For \
example, for the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["2", "nd"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "35851ab0-36fa-4918-adf2-e7b1a5317d74"],
 "-row elements, the cc-pVDZ (correlation-consistent, polarized, valence \
double-zeta) basis set adds an extra set of ",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", and ",
 StyleBox["d",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals to the minimal basis for a total of fourteen basis functions. The \
corresponding valence triple-zeta basis set, cc-pVTZ, adds a further set of ",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox["d",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", and ",
 StyleBox["f",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals to the double-zeta basis for a total of thirty basis functions."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8148825906951866`*^9, 3.814882757469948*^9}, {
  3.814882800839388*^9, 3.8148828484351993`*^9}, {3.814882906004796*^9, 
  3.81488293839602*^9}, {3.814883059119031*^9, 
  3.814883059731498*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"efbd78f3-14d8-40d8-9bb1-\
fd8054e78a7e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Polarization functionality is already built into the basis sets by the \
addition of an extra set of orbitals in the basis set (for example, the extra \
",
 StyleBox["d",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals in the double-zeta basis set). Diffuse functions can also be \
added, which is typically specified by the addition of the prefix ",
 StyleBox["aug",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " to the basis set name (e.g., aug-cc-pVTZ). "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814882975151253*^9, 3.8148831337285023`*^9}, {
  3.8148833969894867`*^9, 
  3.8148833993073626`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f87e78d4-3ddc-45aa-8264-\
0330fd47be3a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The correlation-consistent basis sets are also designed to converge \
smoothly, meaning the energies at each level of calculation can be fitted to \
extrapolate the energy in the complete-basis-set (CBS) limit. This concept is \
illustrated in Figure 12.4. By performing a fit of the energies calculated \
with different sizes of the basis sets, one can extrapolate the hypothetical \
energy with a basis set of infinite size, known as the complete-basis-set \
energy, or ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["E", "CBS"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "904b795c-9416-4c52-ab95-d86a06d1fdd0"],
 ". "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.81488239270052*^9, 3.814882413460759*^9}, 
   3.814882457070506*^9, {3.8148825089449153`*^9, 3.8148825811203537`*^9}, {
   3.8148832685853105`*^9, 3.814883290355262*^9}, {3.814890469272915*^9, 
   3.8148904694362087`*^9}, 
   3.939206146813452*^9},ExpressionUUID->"f28d11a8-6fe1-4131-b574-\
32b6918e264f"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

